00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.903
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Today's
topic is portfolio theory.

00:00:24.903 --> 00:00:32.360
An it's really one of the most
important topics in finance.

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:37.650
We're going to go through the
historical theory of portfolio

00:00:37.650 --> 00:00:41.560
optimization, beginning
with Markowitz Mean-Variance

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:46.170
Optimization, where we
look at portfolios in terms

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:47.670
of their performance
characteristics

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:52.490
as determined by the mean return
and the volatility returns.

00:00:52.490 --> 00:00:56.560
This analysis gets extended
by looking at also investing

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:58.590
with a risk-free asset.

00:00:58.590 --> 00:01:01.080
The initial theory
on portfolio analysis

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:03.370
didn't consider
investing in cash,

00:01:03.370 --> 00:01:05.510
but just investing
in risky assets.

00:01:05.510 --> 00:01:07.310
The problem changes
quite dramatically when

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:09.950
we add the risk-free asset.

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:13.660
Then the topic of utility
theory, von Neumann-Morgenstern

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:19.360
utility theory, in
statistical decision theory,

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:22.710
we are trying to make
decisions under uncertainty

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:24.450
in a rational way.

00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:31.850
And von Neumann and Morgenstern
developed a expected utility

00:01:31.850 --> 00:01:34.640
hypothesis for rational
decision making.

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:36.450
And that's really very
important motivator

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:41.700
for decision analysis generally
and portfolio selection

00:01:41.700 --> 00:01:42.350
in particular.

00:01:42.350 --> 00:01:44.500
So we'll go through that.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:48.240
Then we'll turn to portfolio
optimization constraints.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:51.015
There are realistic issues
when you have-- well,

00:01:51.015 --> 00:01:53.460
there's how much money
you have to invest,

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:55.930
how much capital you have
to invest, whether you could

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:59.715
short securities or not,
whether there are sort

00:01:59.715 --> 00:02:02.190
of limits in capacity
of different assets

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:03.200
you might want to trade.

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:07.610
Those can come into play
and affect the solutions.

00:02:07.610 --> 00:02:11.900
All of these methods
are driven by estimates

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.160
of how well we
expect assets to do,

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:18.910
so estimating returns
or estimating alphas,

00:02:18.910 --> 00:02:22.470
and also estimating the
volatilities and correlations

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:25.130
amongst the assets
were trading in.

00:02:25.130 --> 00:02:27.120
Most of the theory we'll
talk about today deals

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:30.740
with estimates-- well,
with the problem where

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:33.480
we're assuming basically
certainty in terms

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:36.800
of understanding those
underlying return

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:39.330
characteristics, the means,
variances, correlations.

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:43.520
But when we have to estimate
those that raises problems.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:45.020
And finally, we'll
finish up talking

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:47.630
about some alternative
risk measures, which

00:02:47.630 --> 00:02:50.240
extend the
straightforward mean--

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:52.195
or simple
mean-variance analysis.

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:05.060
Now the mean-variance analysis
is a single-period analysis.

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:09.020
What we want to do is
consider investing our capital

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:11.160
in some assets.

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:15.300
And we want to do so
for just a single period

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:18.760
and do so optimally.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:22.880
So in terms of notation,
we'll consider risky assets

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.050
indexed by i, 1 through m.

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:29.970
Single-period returns will
be a multivariate vector

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:32.870
of those returns.

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:37.520
The mean and covariance
of these assets

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:43.793
are represented in vector of
returns and covariance matrix

00:03:43.793 --> 00:03:46.410
of squared volatilities,
the variances

00:03:46.410 --> 00:03:47.930
of the assets along
the diagonals,

00:03:47.930 --> 00:03:49.810
and the covariances
on the off-diagonals.

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:56.840
A portfolio will be represented
as basically a weighting

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:00.340
of our investment
in these m assets.

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:05.780
So we'll have a vector w,
consisting of w_1 up to w_m.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.380
I'm giving the relative
weights and absolute weights

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:10.830
of those investments.

00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:14.110
We'll assume that we have one
unit of capital to invest.

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.579
So the sum of these
weights equals 1.

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:24.060
And the portfolio return
has expected return

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:28.420
given by the expectation
of this linear combination

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:30.990
of the returns, which is simply
the same linear combination

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.040
of the underlying expectations.

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:36.310
And the variance
of the portfolio

00:04:36.310 --> 00:04:39.950
is given by the variance
of the weighted average

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:42.510
of the individual
returns, which is

00:04:42.510 --> 00:04:46.190
given by this quadratic form
in the covariance matrix.

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:51.350
So we've gone through this--
or you understand, I think,

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:54.070
these calculations from our
discussion in time series.

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:57.170
And that's quite simple.

00:04:57.170 --> 00:05:02.310
Now before going into
the theory for this,

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:05.430
let's look at the problem.

00:05:05.430 --> 00:05:08.280
Let's look at the
portfolio analysis problem

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:10.460
in a very simplified setting.

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:13.880
So we're just going
to consider two assets

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.770
and talk about optimal
portfolios investing

00:05:16.770 --> 00:05:18.370
in these two assets.

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:21.410
So m equals 2.

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:25.616
The first asset has
return R_1 with mean 0.15.

00:05:25.616 --> 00:05:28.725
Now I'm going to think of
this as annualized return, so

00:05:28.725 --> 00:05:33.820
a 15% annualized return
and a volatility of 25%.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:38.070
The second asset has
expected return of 20%

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:43.340
and a volatility
of 30%, sigma_2.

00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:46.320
These assets are
possibly correlated.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:50.080
We'll let rho denote the
correlation between the two.

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:53.660
And a portfolio-- basically
all the portfolios

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:57.810
we could invest in, so
long as we are limited

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:01.520
to a unit of capital
and no shorting,

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:04.360
are given by portfolios
indexed by w,

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:07.790
basically the amount of money
we invest in the second asset.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:13.620
So R_w is w R_2
plus 1 minus w R_1.

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:15.780
That's the return
on the portfolio

00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:19.770
that invest in those
proportions in the two assets.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.380
The expected return is
this linear combination,

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:25.540
which is given in matrix
form in the previous page--

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:27.310
or in the lecture notes.

00:06:27.310 --> 00:06:32.120
And the variance, our
squared volatility is what?

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:35.670
It's 1 minus omega
squared times the variance

00:06:35.670 --> 00:06:41.520
of R_1 plus w squared
times the variance of R_2.

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:45.760
Then we have a covariance
term that comes into play.

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:54.030
Now the mean-variance analysis
that Markowitz addressed

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:57.205
basically looks at the
feasible portfolio set.

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:02.890
We simplify things
by saying let's focus

00:07:02.890 --> 00:07:06.770
just on the volatility or
variance and the expected

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:08.810
return of our portfolio.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:12.420
So we can define the
feasible portfolio

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:17.770
set as the collection
of volatility return

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:23.820
pairs for all the assets--
or for all the portfolios.

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:28.980
And well, what is pi
star, that collection?

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:32.050
Basically what's the universe
of possible portfolios

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:33.069
we could construct?

00:07:33.069 --> 00:07:35.360
In this two dimensional case
it's going to very simple.

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:38.270
In multidimensional cases
it's more complicated.

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:40.250
But what portfolios are optimal?

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:42.450
Sub-optimal?

00:07:42.450 --> 00:07:45.690
How do we choose or identify
a particular portfolio

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:46.700
to invest in?

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.270
How's that choice made?

00:07:49.270 --> 00:07:53.990
And is there any special
structure to these portfolios?

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:55.490
What you'll see in
the lecture today

00:07:55.490 --> 00:07:59.490
is that the Markowitz theory
and extensions of that

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:04.520
provide really elegant
answers to these questions.

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:08.190
But let's understand
basically what's going on just

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:11.150
with this two-asset case.

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:15.800
And what I'm going to do
here is just simulate 500

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:20.200
weekly returns with different
values of the correlation

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:23.010
between the two assets.

00:08:23.010 --> 00:08:26.320
And we want to examine
the cumulative returns

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:26.955
of each asset.

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:32.980
The asset returns in terms
of their means, volatilities,

00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:35.580
and correlations,
a plot of pi star,

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:39.330
and the cumulative
returns of each asset

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:40.900
with a minimum
variance portfolio.

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:47.450
So let me just highlight
here that what we want here

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:54.210
is to be plotting sigma_omega
verses alpha_omega.

00:08:56.940 --> 00:09:00.300
And we have two assets.

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:09.660
We have basically sigma_1
and alpha_1 corresponds

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:11.660
to our first asset.

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:17.910
Sigma_2 and alpha_2 corresponds
to our second asset.

00:09:17.910 --> 00:09:31.040
So this point here
corresponds to w equals 0.

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:39.150
And the other corresponds to
w equals 1, so R_1 and R_2.

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:40.810
Now, what's going
to happen when we

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:47.060
combine assets in a portfolio?

00:09:47.060 --> 00:09:54.705
Well, let's take a
look at the simulation.

00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:18.210
OK, here is a graph
of the simulated asset

00:10:18.210 --> 00:10:27.570
returns with basically a mean
returns given by 15%, 25%,

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:32.520
volatility is 20 to 30, and
with an asset correlation of 0.

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:35.400
So here's just a scatter
plot of the weekly returns.

00:10:35.400 --> 00:10:38.586
There's basically no
apparent correlation there.

00:10:38.586 --> 00:10:40.210
There actually is a
sample correlation,

00:10:40.210 --> 00:10:44.580
because a sample from
these distributions

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:48.080
won't have perfectly
0 correlation.

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:52.390
On top, we have graphs of the
cumulative returns of the two

00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:55.200
individual assets.

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.890
Rather obviously,
the higher graph

00:10:57.890 --> 00:11:02.760
corresponds to the asset
with higher return, which

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:03.750
is asset 2.

00:11:03.750 --> 00:11:07.350
And the green
corresponds to asset 1.

00:11:07.350 --> 00:11:09.860
The graph on the
right, top right,

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:15.820
is the graph of the
feasible set as we allocate

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:20.020
between asset 1 and asset 2.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:28.380
And so by the
simulation, this curve

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:32.430
corresponds to the
feasible set of portfolios.

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:41.220
And what's really remarkable
is that we can get basically

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:47.180
a reduction in the
volatility of the portfolio

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:51.310
without compromising,
and in fact improving,

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:54.250
the return the portfolio.

00:11:54.250 --> 00:11:59.260
So if we invest fully in
asset 1, we're at this point.

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:06.470
As we increase-- as we start
allocating towards asset 2,

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:11.120
not only does the return of
asset of the portfolio go up,

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:14.360
but volatility goes down.

00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:20.650
And let's see, in this
simulation, what I've done

00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:26.345
is also plotted the return of
the portfolio corresponding

00:12:26.345 --> 00:12:27.345
to the minimum variance.

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:34.890
So let's just look
the minimum variance

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:42.020
portfolio for a minute.

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:46.040
We have sigma squared
w is equal to 1

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:52.790
minus w squared plus w
squared sigma_2 squared--

00:12:52.790 --> 00:12:55.580
this is sigma 1 squared.

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:58.520
And then plus 0 in
the case there's

00:12:58.520 --> 00:13:01.160
no correlation between
the two assets.

00:13:01.160 --> 00:13:06.720
If we want to minimize
this portfolio volatility,

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:13.150
we can take the derivative of
that with respect to the weight

00:13:13.150 --> 00:13:16.770
and set that equal to 0.

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:18.940
So what's that equal to?

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:26.560
Well, it's-- let's see,
did I do this right?

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:40.080
Actually just with the
previous notes-- sorry,

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:41.600
R_1 is equal to 0.

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:48.340
OK, so we have 2, 1 minus w
sigma_1 squared times minus 1,

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:54.260
plus 2 w sigma_2
squared is equal to 0.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:14:09.680
And so solving this, we get
w is equal to-- well, let's

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:15.670
see, you get 1 over
sigma_1 squared-- sorry,

00:14:15.670 --> 00:14:18.740
1 over sigma_2 squared
divided by 1 over sigma_1

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:21.290
squared plus 1 over
sigma_2 squared.

00:14:21.290 --> 00:14:24.800
If you solve this
out, you basically

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:29.250
get a weighting on the different
assets, which weights them

00:14:29.250 --> 00:14:34.200
inversely proportional to
their squared volatility.

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:38.390
And with this
graph here, you can

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:43.760
see that the blue graph is a bit
closer to asset 1 than to asset

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:46.050
2's cumulative return.

00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:49.470
That corresponds to giving to a
slightly higher weight to asset

00:14:49.470 --> 00:14:53.970
1, because 1 over
sigma_1 squared

00:14:53.970 --> 00:14:57.840
is bigger than 1
over sigma_2 squared.

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:02.190
Well, let's look at
what happens if we

00:15:02.190 --> 00:15:04.630
consider negative correlations
between the two assets.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.590
Well, actually, OK,
before we do that,

00:15:11.590 --> 00:15:14.630
if you were going to choose
one of these portfolios

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:19.550
for investing, are
there any portfolios

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:20.840
that you wouldn't invest in?

00:15:23.928 --> 00:15:27.757
And are any of these
portfolios sub-optimal

00:15:27.757 --> 00:15:28.840
in terms of mean-variance?

00:15:31.684 --> 00:15:33.110
AUDIENCE: w1.

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:37.380
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Well,
w1 is certainly infeasible

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:39.915
because we can increase
its mean and we

00:15:39.915 --> 00:15:42.280
can decrease it's volatility.

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:48.270
So actually all of
these points here

00:15:48.270 --> 00:15:52.060
are really sub-optimal
portfolios.

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:54.690
And from the minimum
variance portfolio,

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:59.530
which is basically getting
us the vertical tangent, all

00:15:59.530 --> 00:16:04.255
the points from here up
to the asset 2, fully

00:16:04.255 --> 00:16:08.440
investing in asset
2 are feasible.

00:16:08.440 --> 00:16:11.650
And none of these portfolios
dominates the other.

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:15.175
Basically it's a trade-off
between return and volatility.

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:21.890
OK, so that's a really important
point that there really

00:16:21.890 --> 00:16:28.470
are portfolios that you can
just disregard considering

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:32.840
that there are definite-- well,
when there's zero correlation,

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:35.430
there is a benefit to
diversifying across these two

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:36.700
assets.

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:41.830
So if you have an asset
and you are considering

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:45.070
pooling that asset with
another in your portfolio,

00:16:45.070 --> 00:16:47.900
if those are fully
uncorrelated, then

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:51.540
you should be able to
improve your portfolio

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:55.720
by adding some allocation
to that second asset.

00:16:55.720 --> 00:17:06.250
Let's look at the a more
negative correlation

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:08.960
between the two
assets of minus 0.4.

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:14.160
Here, you'll see that
there's basically

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:18.300
a tilt, negative tilt, to
the scatter plot of returns.

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:22.310
And with the portfolios
of two assets,

00:17:22.310 --> 00:17:26.319
basically, the feasible
set, that feasible set

00:17:26.319 --> 00:17:31.910
is actually stretching
further to the left.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:35.880
So with a negative correlation
between the assets,

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:40.960
we're actually able to reduce
the volatility even more,

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:44.930
if that's what is
our preference.

00:17:44.930 --> 00:17:52.830
If we go up here to minus 0.8,
it gets even more exaggerated.

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:56.160
Now what's going to
happen if we have

00:17:56.160 --> 00:18:01.330
a correlation of negative
1 between these two assets?

00:18:01.330 --> 00:18:03.315
AUDIENCE: The
portfolio can have 0?

00:18:03.315 --> 00:18:05.690
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Yes, then
a portfolio of the two assets

00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:06.880
can have zero variability.

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:14.550
So indeed with the
hedging strategies,

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:18.150
one often is considering
investing in assets consisting

00:18:18.150 --> 00:18:22.910
of perhaps an underlying
security and some derivative

00:18:22.910 --> 00:18:23.520
on that.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:26.740
And that derivative,
if it's a future say,

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:29.140
could have basically a
negative 1 correlation.

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:32.230
So you could essentially
hedge out the volatility

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:33.320
almost perfectly.

00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:37.900
So that special case actually
does exist quite frequently

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:40.120
and is exploited.

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:43.070
But it falls out just
from the simple analysis

00:18:43.070 --> 00:18:46.570
of this simple simulation.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:51.530
OK, let's also look at the going
to increase in the correlation.

00:18:51.530 --> 00:18:52.030
Yes.

