01:09:18.029 --> 01:09:20.660
Basically, these allocations
are slowly scaling up,

01:09:20.660 --> 01:09:21.714
just linearly.

01:09:21.714 --> 01:09:24.529
And that corresponds
to investing

01:09:24.529 --> 01:09:30.240
in the optimal portfolio without
constraints with a fixed value.

01:09:30.240 --> 01:09:34.760
But once we hit the 30%
then that constraint

01:09:34.760 --> 01:09:36.189
starts to be active.

01:09:36.189 --> 01:09:37.689
And we can't invest
anymore in that.

01:09:37.689 --> 01:09:41.160
So we have to add more
to other securities.

01:09:41.160 --> 01:09:49.300
And so basically more is given
to the consumers discretionary

01:09:49.300 --> 01:09:50.200
and the other.

01:09:50.200 --> 01:09:53.760
Now actually here's another
graph of the same data,

01:09:53.760 --> 01:09:57.400
just stacking the allocation.

01:09:57.400 --> 01:10:02.220
So we consider ranging from how
are we investing our capital.

01:10:02.220 --> 01:10:05.860
This dark red is how much
money we invest in cash.

01:10:05.860 --> 01:10:08.240
And then these
colored lines indicate

01:10:08.240 --> 01:10:10.920
by their vertical
length how much

01:10:10.920 --> 01:10:15.120
we're investing in the
different exchange traded funds.

01:10:15.120 --> 01:10:20.190
So basically as
the constraints get

01:10:20.190 --> 01:10:24.110
hit, the portfolio
sort of change

01:10:24.110 --> 01:10:26.230
in terms of their
overall structure.

01:10:26.230 --> 01:10:32.160
And what can happen
is-- actually

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:35.720
as we're trying to achieve
more and more return,

01:10:35.720 --> 01:10:38.010
well, there may
not be assets that

01:10:38.010 --> 01:10:40.390
provide that additional
return, or there

01:10:40.390 --> 01:10:43.610
may be a very few assets
that provide that return.

01:10:43.610 --> 01:10:47.910
And so in this case,
technology stocks

01:10:47.910 --> 01:10:49.820
are coming in as
we're trying to get

01:10:49.820 --> 01:10:54.050
really high levels of return
in our optimal portfolios.

01:10:54.050 --> 01:10:58.880
And so if we really
want that higher return,

01:10:58.880 --> 01:11:01.840
that's going to
come at higher risk.

01:11:01.840 --> 01:11:04.490
And we actually
are de-allocating

01:11:04.490 --> 01:11:11.560
some from the consumer staples
and consumer discretionary

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:12.970
at that point.

01:11:19.540 --> 01:11:27.000
OK, here's a graph of the
efficient frontier as estimated

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:29.520
with the data.

01:11:29.520 --> 01:11:33.900
And what you can see is
that these portfolios,

01:11:33.900 --> 01:11:37.090
optimal portfolios,
yield improvements

01:11:37.090 --> 01:11:39.820
over each of the individual
exchange-traded funds,

01:11:39.820 --> 01:11:42.930
in terms of having higher
return with lower risk.

01:11:49.050 --> 01:11:52.990
And if we consider just a
target return of 10%-- OK,

01:11:52.990 --> 01:11:54.960
there's the portfolio.

01:11:54.960 --> 01:11:57.350
I've graphed here
sort of in solid blue

01:11:57.350 --> 01:12:02.620
what the optimal portfolio
with a 10% volatility.

01:12:02.620 --> 01:12:06.450
That's the solid
blue line there.

01:12:06.450 --> 01:12:14.370
So these are the results with
this 30% capital constraint.

01:12:14.370 --> 01:12:16.540
Now how is this
problem going to change

01:12:16.540 --> 01:12:20.811
if we reduce the capital
constraint from 30% per asset

01:12:20.811 --> 01:12:21.310
to 15%?

01:12:27.050 --> 01:12:31.582
Who can comment on
what will change?

01:12:31.582 --> 01:12:33.037
AUDIENCE: I'm a little confused.

01:12:33.037 --> 01:12:35.120
Could you put a constraint
on the risk-free asset.

01:12:35.120 --> 01:12:36.203
Could you do that as well?

01:12:41.360 --> 01:12:46.570
PETER KEMPTHORNE: Well, the
risk-free asset has no risk.

01:12:46.570 --> 01:12:50.122
And so putting a
constraint-- well,

01:12:50.122 --> 01:12:52.080
you could put a constraint
on it in terms of it

01:12:52.080 --> 01:12:55.010
not going negative and it
not being greater than one.

01:12:55.010 --> 01:12:56.430
So in fact that is a constraint.

01:12:56.430 --> 01:12:58.138
Those are constraints
being imposed here.

01:13:03.770 --> 01:13:09.150
But, I guess, in some-- well,
there are, like I guess,

01:13:09.150 --> 01:13:11.960
endowments, say, that have
investment policies that

01:13:11.960 --> 01:13:15.480
say that they want a certain
fraction assets invested

01:13:15.480 --> 01:13:17.210
in risky assets and not in cash.

01:13:17.210 --> 01:13:23.190
So that is a
realistic constraint

01:13:23.190 --> 01:13:25.510
in certain circumstances.

01:13:25.510 --> 01:13:30.890
And this is just highlighting
how the allocations vary

01:13:30.890 --> 01:13:32.950
across the risky
asset if we only

01:13:32.950 --> 01:13:37.000
have very simple constraints
on the cash investment.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:41.030
Well, the question
I want to focus on

01:13:41.030 --> 01:13:44.542
is what happens if we make
the maximum allocation

01:13:44.542 --> 01:13:45.500
constraint more severe.

01:13:45.500 --> 01:13:47.580
So it's 15% instead of 30%.

01:13:47.580 --> 01:13:55.030
Then what's going to happen is
these capital constraints are

01:13:55.030 --> 01:13:57.820
going to start hitting sooner.

01:13:57.820 --> 01:14:03.320
So we have to allocate to the
other exchange traded funds.

01:14:03.320 --> 01:14:06.937
So let me show you how that
works out with the same graph.

01:14:10.520 --> 01:14:24.500
Let's see-- OK, let me just
close that and then we go here.

01:14:28.010 --> 01:14:31.120
OK, this shows with
a 15% allocation,

01:14:31.120 --> 01:14:34.270
how the allocations vary.

01:14:34.270 --> 01:14:39.890
And I'll be posting this
on the course website.

01:14:39.890 --> 01:14:44.950
But it turns out the efficient
frontier is actually lower.

01:14:44.950 --> 01:14:48.390
Basically, for higher
returns, we actually

01:14:48.390 --> 01:14:51.571
can't get those higher
returns by getting

01:14:51.571 --> 01:14:52.820
the biggest bang for the buck.

01:14:52.820 --> 01:14:55.480
We don't want to allocate
too much to those higher

01:14:55.480 --> 01:14:57.620
return, higher risk securities.

01:14:57.620 --> 01:15:03.070
And so the optimal, the
efficient frontier as estimated

01:15:03.070 --> 01:15:05.520
basically slopes down.

01:15:05.520 --> 01:15:15.840
Now, with this
particular example

01:15:15.840 --> 01:15:19.230
of these exchange-traded
funds and how

01:15:19.230 --> 01:15:23.210
you allocate across those,
this provides some insight

01:15:23.210 --> 01:15:26.990
into portfolio optimization.

01:15:26.990 --> 01:15:29.700
It's not really a
realistic setting,

01:15:29.700 --> 01:15:31.310
because we're
looking over the past

01:15:31.310 --> 01:15:33.860
and using the actual
sample performance

01:15:33.860 --> 01:15:36.820
to define these portfolios.

01:15:36.820 --> 01:15:42.680
Let me just highlight an
example of applying these kinds

01:15:42.680 --> 01:15:51.440
of methods with a-- is it here?

01:15:51.440 --> 01:15:51.980
Yep, OK.

01:16:04.642 --> 01:16:07.077
Is that the right graph?

01:16:10.490 --> 01:16:16.170
OK, suppose we
consider not investing

01:16:16.170 --> 01:16:17.860
in exchange-traded funds.

