That actually is
the utility sector.

01:18:00.140 --> 01:18:13.210
And then these other models
are industrials and energy.

01:18:13.210 --> 01:18:29.070
And so if we consider
investing in these,

01:18:29.070 --> 01:18:33.580
we can actually achieve a
target volatility of 10%--

01:18:33.580 --> 01:18:36.370
we're going to achieve
this solid blue line--

01:18:36.370 --> 01:18:39.090
as the portfolio strategy.

01:18:39.090 --> 01:18:43.250
And one can see how by combining
these assets together--

01:18:43.250 --> 01:18:46.190
these assets are different
market-neutral trading

01:18:46.190 --> 01:18:49.660
models-- we have to get
quite a bit of benefit

01:18:49.660 --> 01:18:52.830
from the portfolio optimization.

01:18:52.830 --> 01:18:56.000
And the greater benefit in
the portfolio optimization

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:02.114
is because these strategies tend
to have much lower correlations

01:19:02.114 --> 01:19:02.780
with each other.

01:19:07.240 --> 01:19:22.821
Let's go back now, finish up
with-- how do we go back here?

01:19:26.300 --> 01:19:28.288
Where's my red dot?

01:20:06.640 --> 01:20:15.650
OK, just to finish up the
discussion, with these methods

01:20:15.650 --> 01:20:18.300
it's important to highlight
that what we've been using

01:20:18.300 --> 01:20:20.690
were estimated returns,
estimated volatilities,

01:20:20.690 --> 01:20:21.830
and correlations.

01:20:21.830 --> 01:20:27.720
And these estimates can have
a huge impact on the results.

01:20:27.720 --> 01:20:30.310
There's basically choices
of estimation period.

01:20:30.310 --> 01:20:32.540
There's estimation error.

01:20:32.540 --> 01:20:37.790
Different techniques can
modulate these issues.

01:20:37.790 --> 01:20:40.090
Exponential moving
average are often applied.

01:20:40.090 --> 01:20:44.590
Having dynamic factor
models is used.

01:20:44.590 --> 01:20:46.494
Basically, rather than
using sample estimates

01:20:46.494 --> 01:20:47.910
of the variance/covariance
matrix,

01:20:47.910 --> 01:20:52.120
using factor models to estimate
the variance-covariance matrix

01:20:52.120 --> 01:20:59.450
results in more precise
inputs to the optimization.

01:20:59.450 --> 01:21:03.834
And finally, just with
different risk measures--

01:21:03.834 --> 01:21:05.625
we've been focusing on
portfolio volatility

01:21:05.625 --> 01:21:10.180
and minimizing that-- the
methodologies can be extended

01:21:10.180 --> 01:21:13.010
to have different
measures of risk--

01:21:13.010 --> 01:21:17.330
mean absolute deviation, for
example, or semi-variance.

01:21:19.860 --> 01:21:24.230
In terms of the motivation
for squared volatility

01:21:24.230 --> 01:21:29.100
and minimizing that, you'll
recall that in likelihood

01:21:29.100 --> 01:21:31.746
analysis of Gaussian
distributions,

01:21:31.746 --> 01:21:33.620
the sort of squared
deviations from the means

01:21:33.620 --> 01:21:36.390
are characterizing variability.

01:21:36.390 --> 01:21:40.870
Well, if we focus on mean
absolute deviation, then

01:21:40.870 --> 01:21:44.440
probability distributions
where the distributions relate

01:21:44.440 --> 01:21:47.072
to the absolute deviation
from the mean characterizing

01:21:47.072 --> 01:21:49.720
the distribution
might be appropriate.

01:21:49.720 --> 01:21:54.460
And indeed, distributions
with heavier tails,

01:21:54.460 --> 01:21:58.000
like exponential
distributions, are

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:00.410
appropriate when we consider
mean absolute deviation.

01:22:00.410 --> 01:22:02.840
So some alternate
risk measures are

01:22:02.840 --> 01:22:05.260
appropriate when the
volatility measure

01:22:05.260 --> 01:22:09.710
itself isn't necessarily
appropriate because

01:22:09.710 --> 01:22:12.400
of the distributional
assumptions.

01:22:12.400 --> 01:22:15.860
Semi-variance was introduced
actually by Markowitz,

01:22:15.860 --> 01:22:18.590
where you're interested in
controlling the downside risk

01:22:18.590 --> 01:22:20.140
as opposed to the upside risk.

01:22:22.990 --> 01:22:25.540
There's value-at-risk
measures which

01:22:25.540 --> 01:22:30.280
are now completely standard
in portfolio management

01:22:30.280 --> 01:22:38.700
and management of risky assets,
where one is actually-- well,

01:22:38.700 --> 01:22:40.335
this is introduced
by Ken Abbott in one

01:22:40.335 --> 01:22:42.270
of the first few lectures.

01:22:42.270 --> 01:22:46.600
Value at risk is
a very simple idea

01:22:46.600 --> 01:22:51.850
of characterizing
what outcome is

01:22:51.850 --> 01:22:54.940
sort of the threshold
of extreme, at say

01:22:54.940 --> 01:22:58.840
the 5% level or the 1%
level, and to basically keep

01:22:58.840 --> 01:23:00.520
and monitor the value at risk.

01:23:00.520 --> 01:23:03.390
So if we had a risk
that was basically

01:23:03.390 --> 01:23:06.610
in the worst 5%
or 1% of the time.

01:23:06.610 --> 01:23:08.130
What is that level?

01:23:08.130 --> 01:23:10.600
That's the value at risk.

01:23:10.600 --> 01:23:17.130
That as a nice risk measure is
simple to define and reasonably

01:23:17.130 --> 01:23:19.400
simple to estimate.

01:23:19.400 --> 01:23:22.950
But it doesn't characterize sort
of what the potential exposure

01:23:22.950 --> 01:23:24.680
is if you exceed that.

01:23:24.680 --> 01:23:26.060
And there are
extensions of that.

01:23:26.060 --> 01:23:28.730
The conditional
value at risk which

01:23:28.730 --> 01:23:32.480
is looking at the
expected loss given

01:23:32.480 --> 01:23:35.230
that you exceed the
value at risk threshold.

01:23:35.230 --> 01:23:40.040
And this method is
now-- I think it's

01:23:40.040 --> 01:23:47.950
been going to be incorporated
into regulatory requirements

01:23:47.950 --> 01:23:50.180
for banks in terms of
how they measure risk.

01:23:50.180 --> 01:23:53.950
Right now, I believe it's
almost all value at risk.

01:23:53.950 --> 01:23:56.670
Extensions like this
conditional value at risk

01:23:56.670 --> 01:24:00.900
is definitely going
to be applied.

01:24:00.900 --> 01:24:04.220
And in the discussion of
different risk measures,

01:24:04.220 --> 01:24:05.840
there's literature
talking about what

01:24:05.840 --> 01:24:08.630
are appropriate risk measures
and how do we define those.

01:24:08.630 --> 01:24:13.010
Well, it really depends
on what your assets are

01:24:13.010 --> 01:24:20.190
and if your assets are simply
simple investments in stocks

01:24:20.190 --> 01:24:25.720
or bonds, sort of cash
assets or cash instruments,

01:24:25.720 --> 01:24:28.530
then value at risk
is quite reasonable.

01:24:28.530 --> 01:24:30.890
If you're investing
in derivatives,

01:24:30.890 --> 01:24:36.135
which have non-linear payoffs,
then things get complicated.

01:24:36.135 --> 01:24:42.900
And so things need to be handled
on a case by case basis there.

01:24:42.900 --> 01:24:45.174
But if you're interested
in risk analysis,

01:24:45.174 --> 01:24:47.340
there's a whole discussion
on coherent risk measures

01:24:47.340 --> 01:24:50.479
that you can look into.

01:24:50.479 --> 01:24:51.520
That's quite interesting.

01:24:51.520 --> 01:24:52.720
OK, let's stop there.

01:24:52.720 --> 01:24:54.570
Thank you.

